From: iwj10@cus.cam.ac.uk (Ian Jackson)
Subject: Re: Please do NOT reply mail
Date: Wed, 27 Oct 1993 02:13:55 GMT

In article <2ahpjs$au@victrola.wa.com>,
Vince Skahan <vince@victrola.wa.com> wrote:
>My personal opinion is that asking for followups via mail or setting a
>Followups-To: or Reply-To: header is perfectly fine and not rude in the
>least.  Ian disagrees.  That doesn't mean either of us is a bad person
>(or that either of us is 'correct'...)

I think Vince has misunderstood me.

Asking for replies by mail is rude if you're doing it because you
can't be bothered to read the group looking for your answer.

My statement, that you took issue with (well, quoted, anyway):
>>If you do not have read access to Usenet you should not post.
>>Period.
is perfectly true.  Anyone who does not agree with this needs to read
news.announce.newusers.

However (as I believe I said earlier) asking for replies by mail so
that you can build and post a summary is a good idea, even though it
appears to be out of fashion in the generally netiquetteless
comp.os.linux hierarchy.

Oh, and I wouldn't suggest that my time was more valuable than Vince's
(or indeed than that of anyone involved with the Linux community, as
developer or user).  I just don't think that the average questioner's
time is worth 10 or 100 times the average reader's.

