From: becker@super.org (Donald J. Becker)
Subject: Re: SLIP/plip - HowTO Disable???
Date: Tue, 26 Oct 1993 05:08:58 GMT

In article <2ah7fuINNg85@ope001.iao.ford.com>,
Eric Kimminau <ekimmina@pms709.pms.ford.com> wrote:
>Greetings!
>
>On bootup, I get a few lines saying SLIP is enabled, and then plip0-2
>running on IRQ's 5,7, and 2.I have my bus mous on IRQ/2, My sound
>blaster on 5, and LPT1 is on 7. I just KNOW this is causing part of my
>problems with X and my bus mouse. How do I disable this plip, whatever
>the heck it is??? Ive manned everything under the sun and can't find
>anything to do with plip or SLIP...

Unless PLIP is enabled, and it almost certainly isn't, it won't affect other
parts of your system.  PLIP is reporting the interrupt line that it _would_ use
if started, not that it _is_ using the interrupt line.

You bus mouse problems are likely elsewhere, probably that the bus mouse
driver is always trying to use IRQ5 rather than doing an autoIRQ for the
correct interrupt line.  I've run into this myself when installing a system
for someone, and it was difficult to track down.

I would write the bus-mouse autoIRQ code myself, if I had one to test with.
It is as simple as adding an 'int irq;' field to <linux/busmouse.h>,
and some code like the following to drivers/char/*mouse.c:mouse_init()

...
        autoirq_setup(1);
        MS_MSE_INT_ON();        /* Trigger an interrupt by twinkling */
        MS_MSE_INT_OFF();       /* the jumpered interrupt line.  */
        mouse.irq = autoirq_report(0);

        if (mouse.irq == 0) {
                mouse.present = 0;
        else {
                printk("Microsoft BusMouse detected at %#x on IRQ %d.\n",
                        MS_MSE_DATA_PORT, mouse.irq);
                snarf_region(MS_MSE_DATA_PORT, 4);
        }
        return kmem_start;
}  

-- 

Donald Becker                                          becker@super.org
IDA Supercomputing Research Center
17100 Science Drive, Bowie MD 20715                        301-805-7482

