From: t933093@minyos.xx.rmit.OZ.AU (Hamish Glen Coleman)
Subject: Re: Optimizing Swap Space
Date: 27 Oct 1993 13:49:43 GMT

mdgauthi@rodan.syr.edu (Elleron) writes:

>       I wonder, is anyone using swap partions on different drives to
>speed up the time? Or do any kernel wizards have an opinion on this?

Now, this is something that I have jsut started to think about myself.

I have just added a second hard-drive to one of my systems that is 1:1
interleave, and the old drive is 3:1 interleave, so I stuck a 4M swapfile
onto it and made sure that that partition was swapon'd first.  Kernel
compiles (wonderful benchmark eh?) now are noticeably faster, going from
approx 1 and a half hours to approx 1 hour and 15 mins (i know, its
not much),....

But, I was thinking to myself, swapping should be able to take advantage
of multi-tasking, and if I added a 3rd drive, and stuck a swapfile on 
that, then I should get a speed up even if the new drive was just as slow
as any existing ones..

All that a simple implementation would need would be to jump to the next
swapfile when the kernel starts to search for a free swap page.  I think
that I will have to look further into this..

Does anyone have any ideas of what a real mothod of swapfile load balancing
should look like??

Hamish


