From: karlcz@OCF.Berkeley.EDU (Karl F. Czajkowski)
Subject: Re: Bogomip
Date: 27 Oct 1993 15:45:06 GMT

In article <CFJr60.JA1@newsserver.technet.sg>,
Mathias Koerber <mathias@solomon.technet.sg> wrote:
>In (<1993Oct24.172843.4969@gulasch.hanse.de>) Elmar Folba (elmar@gulasch.hanse.de) wrote:
>| Remember, folks, that in mass production the properties of the goods produced
>| follow some distribution - within specified limits. In the market we are
>| talking about you can expect those limits to be pretty wide, too: I'd
>| consider 5% off the nominal value still pretty normal.
>| Therefore, if you wonder about BogoMips(tm), try Norton Utilities'
>| SYSINFO: you'll be surprised about the differences you'll get betweeen
>| not only identical processor chips, but motherboards of the same brand, etc.

>| I won't bother you with neither BogoMips(tm) nor the SYSINFO value of my
>| 386/40.

>But how do you explain 2 diff. BogoMips on the exact same machine? One is
>from SLS1.03 (33.55) and the other from Slackware 1.04 (33.22). Do they use
>diff? algorithms or so?

>Mathias

I suppose I should have looked at the source for the kernel to be sure of
how BogoMips are calculated, i.e. external interrupts or what, but I will
just speculate away.  Assuming a loop which simply increments a counter
is running until it is stopped by a real-time syncronized interrupt, then
a variation in either the realtime clock or the clock crystal (the one
that make it a 40MHz board) would skew these values.  So consider that
the rule for manufacturing quality distribution applies to both the real
time clock chip, the crystal, and everything else too!

On my cheap 386DX-33 the BogoMips varies up to .07 BogoMips between boots,
and my CMOS clock loses tens of minutes in less than a month.

Karl C.

[sorry if I messed up the credits, that was one convoluted chain of quotes.]

